text.tspan: 22Use ofAsbestosIMOSOLAS Ch II-1 Regulation3-5.2Prohibits all newinstallations ofasbestos on boardships, withoutexceptions and IMOwill have itscommittee for Designand Equipment todevelopment adefinition of the term"new installation ofmaterials” whetherthis includeinstallation of spareparts alreadyonboard or not.It is envisaged thatthe total prohibitionapplies both to newand existing ships.The availability ofsuch replacementparts that do notcontain asbestos aswell as the status ofthe spare parts thatare alreadypurchased mayrequire carefulconsideration.However anyphysical installationafter 1 January 2011onboard cargo shipsof 500 GT or moreengaged oninternational voyagewill not be allowed.ESM/ VesselOffice toensureasbestos freeequipmentsupply tovesselYesDuring ship visitto check3CONTRACT MANAGEMENT3.1COMPANY'S POLICY FOR CONTRACT MANAGEMENTThe aim of the Company is to enter into ventures in which the Company has competency and justify that it is capable of doing so.Importance is given to the fact that entering into contracts with any ship owner, does not in any manner, lead to conflict of businessinterests with other clients.3.2PROCEDURES FOR VESSEL’S CONTRACT MANAGEMENT1) When an inquiry is received from a new customer, a background check is to be carried out to ensure that the customer is genuineand not seeking information for his use for clandestine purposes, on the pretext of giving management of ships to company. Anybudgets or financial data shall only be provided after establishing authenticity and getting the Managing Director’s approval.2) It shall be verified whether in-house expertise is available for the business offered.3) Prime importance shall also be given to ascertain whether or not the vessel to be managed falls within the scope of the Company'spolicies and objectives.4) The customer shall allow the inspection of the vessel by the Technical Superintendent or should provide inspection report by areputable third party along with the Class records prior vessel is accepted for management.5) Subsequent to the Technical Superintendent's inspection a budget shall be provided to the owner along with the upgrading and pre-operating cost. If however budget is prepared based on the Inspection Report of the third party, then the budget shall be claused,stating revised budget shall be provided after the vessel has been inspected.6) Due consideration shall be given to safety and environment protection aspects as existing on the vessels and allowance foraddressing any shortfalls / deficiencies shall be made in the budget.7) Differences between the conditions in the contract and those previously expressed are to be resolved.8) The Management Agreement is thereafter sent to the customer for their approval and signature.3.3MANAGEMENT CONTRACTIn summary, Management of a vessel by the Company refers to the following services:1) To take care of the husbandry details relating to the vessel's operations.2) To look after the recruitment, training and the employment of officers and crew of the vessel.3) To ensure that the vessel is adequately stocked with stores, spares, lubricant etc. at all times for safe operation.4) To ensure that the vessel's class is maintained at all times and to repair and maintain the machinery in an efficient and seaworthycondition including dry-docking.5) To supply the Owner with account statements, operating and technical data on a regular basis.
